Project Overview 1
Have you ever wondered why:

Air temperatures over land and sea surface temperature is increasing?
Sea levels are rising and snow is decreasing?
Rain  and Snow Patterns are changing?
Ocean acidity is increasing?
Humidity is increasing?
Trees are flowering sooner?

Global climate change are having more observable effects on the environment as the emissions of greenhouse gases(GHG) continue to increase globally. The emissions of Greenhouse gases have been a major problem since the beginning of the Industrial Revolution due to human activities worldwide. Their concentrations have increased significantly and because these gases trap heat and stay in the atmosphere for tens to hundreds of years after being released, their warming effects on the climate persist over a long time and can therefore affect both present and future generations.  Greenhouse gases have far-ranging environmental and health effects. They cause climate change by trapping heat, and they also contribute to respiratory disease from smog and air pollution. Extreme weather, food supply disruptions, and increased wildfires are other effects of climate change caused by greenhouse gases.
Some countries produce far more greenhouse gases than others, and this can be attributed to several factors such as economic activity (including the composition and efficiency of the economy), population, income level, land use, and climatic conditions—can influence a country’s emissions level. 
This project focuses to analyze total Greenhouse gases emitted by each Country, the growth/decline in emissions per year, the Greenhouse gas per capita(tonnes per person) for each  Country and the growth/decline in emissions per capita based on various industry sectors and four major GHG gases - CO2, CH4, NO2 and F2O.



Problem Statement:

Worldwide, the output of greenhouse gases is a source of grave concern. Recent studies documented in the United Nations Environment Program(UNEP) Emissions Gap Report 2018 shows that GHG emissions are growing globally despite progress in climate policy as the countries where emissions are declining are not able to offset the growth in emissions in other countries. GHG emissions of the major gases increased by an average of 1.3% per year over the last decade and unless all countries adopt efficient and sustainable strategies to reduce their GHG emissions, there would be detrimental effects to climate change.
